Defendant Clifford Beasley in court with attorney Thomas John Erickson.  Defendant Clifford Beasley in custody.  Benjamin A. Wesson appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Deputy Court Clerk: dds.

Defendant prepared to enter change of plea.  Hearing proceeded.  Negotiations set forth by the state.

AS TO COUNTS 1, 2, 3, AND 4:  The defendant was advised of his constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, plead GUILTY and was examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights, Addendum to Plea Questionnaire, and Jury Instructions received and filed.  The parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis for the plea.  The Court found the defendant guilty and ordered entry of Judgment of Conviction.  Pursuant to Wisconsin Statutes Section 973.176, the Court advised the defendant of the following restrictions:  Firearm possession and Voting.  Filed, Ineligible Voting Notice and Acknowledgement.  

AS TO COUNTS 5 and 6:  Pursuant to plea negotiations and on motion of the state, the Court ordered Counts 5 and 6 DISMISSED AND READ-IN for the purpose of sentencing in Counts 1-4.  

Sentencing proceeded.  Statements made by State, Shelina H., defense, and defendant. 
 
AS TO COUNT 1:  The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 8 YEARS, CONSECUTIVE to any other sentence with credit for 178 days served. The INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 4 YEARS.  The MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION IS 4 YEARS.

AS TO COUNT 2:  The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 4 YEARS, CONSECUTIVE to Counts 1, 3, 4, and any other sentence with credit for 0 days served. The INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 2 YEARS.  The MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION IS 2 YEARS.

AS TO COUNT 3:  The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 2 YEARS, CONSECUTIVE to Counts 1, 2, 4, and any other sentence with credit for 0 days served. The INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 1 YEAR.  The MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION IS 1 YEAR.

AS TO COUNT 4:  The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 4 YEARS, CONSECUTIVE to Counts 1, 2, 3 and with any other sentence with credit for 0 days served. The INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 2 YEARS.  The MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION IS 2 YEARS.

The defendant IS eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program and the Substance Abuse Program ONLY AFTER SERVING THE FIRST 5 YEARS OF THESE SENTENCES.

AS TO  COUNTS 1-4:  CONDITIONS OF  EXTENDED SUPERVISION:
*Referral to Mental health division for mental assessment and if necessary, successfully complete follow-up treatment;
*Take any medication prescribed only in the manner/dosage as prescribed by treating physician;
*Obtain AODA assessment and successfully complete follow-up treatment;
*Cooperate with random urine screens;
*No drug dealing or association with drug community (drug users/dealers or drug houses);
*Cooperate with any and all rules set forth by the probation agent;
*No new law violations rising to the level of probable cause;
*Participate in Cognitive Thinking program;
*No contact with victims John L., Ashley F., Tiffany J., Jabalja L., Shelina H., Paul H., Debra A., and Community Financial Service Center located at 2652 W. Fond du Lac Ave.;
*Obtain/maintain full time employment or full time school and part time employment;
*Pay all supervision fees;
*Provide DNA sample- pay surcharge;
*Pay all mandatory applicable surcharges, fees, assessments, and costs; 

State in compliance with victim rights legislation.  The Court ordered restitution in the stipulated amount of $1600 payable to Jabalja L- to be paid first.  The Court ordered that all financial obligations and restitution be paid through collection of sums by the Department of Corrections from 25% of funds under Sec. 973.05(4)(b) and as a condition of extended supervision.  Any amount remaining due and owing is subject to civil judgment.  Pursuant to Wisconsin Statutes Section 973.176, the Court advised the defendant of the following restrictions:  Firearm possession and Voting. Appeal rights given by the court.
